{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_carpsurprise_ver01/data/sn85009852/00517174774/1945082401/0382.xml":{"full_text":"FOUR\nEast Hartforb ftazettr\nEstablished 1885\nPUBLISHED EVERY FRIDAY AT\nEAST HARTFORD, CONN.\nBy The Gazette Publishing Company\nEDWARD B. STEVENS\nPublisher\nDANIEL F. SHEA\nEditor si\nHENRI TUSSENBROEK\nAssociate Editor\nEntered at the Post Office in East Hartford as\nSecond Class Matter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES:\nFull Year $2.00\nSix Months sl-25\nThree Months 75c\nSingle Copy 4c\nNATIONAL DITORI AL_\nw associat'on\nRECONVERSION AND LABOR\nWhen the first announcements of the Japa\nnese surrender came, the complicated picture of\nAmerican war activities swung momentarily into a\nsudden halt.\nIt seemed but a matter of hours before we\nknew that attempts at the reorganization of indus\ntry were already in full swing.\nA first analysis of the dramatic steps along the\nproduction front revealed the colossal scope of the\nwar effort up to the very minute of surrender by\nthe enemy.\nIt appeared like a signal to all industry to\nstop at once, take inventory, turn about face and\nhead back on the road to reconversion.\nThe program which lies ahead is of neces\nsity based on many new factors and ideas. Revolu\ntionary discoveries in science, a quick and compre\nhensive picture of the most immediate needs for the\ncountry, the availability of new materials and the\nconsiderations for the returning servicemen all will\ndemand a certain amount of time for readjustment.\nNo reasonable thinking person can expect in\ndustry to keep going ahead full steam on orders\nwhich are cancelled by sheer necessity. The temp\norary layoffs are merely the moment for big indus\ntry to take a new breath and start all over again on\nits new mission, reconversion and production.\nThere is no reason for alarm. The stock of\nessential necessities for living is at a new low. The\nproblems of the world at large will demand nation\nal production on a scale far beyond pre-war pro\nduction.\nThe announcement by Secretary of Labor\nSchwellenback in regard to the passing of the little\nsteel formula carried with it some weighty consid\nrations for labor. Price level control will revert to\nindustry on the condition that no increase in prices\nwill follow.\nThe period of the war behind us has unfor\ntunately brought with it some ill adjustments in our\nnational economy. Like in all upheavals of this\nkind there have been those whose earnings were\nnever in the proper ratio to the cost of living.\nIn the new national economy it will be neces\nsary to even out the possibilities for national pros\nperity in such a manner that the new standards of\nliving, promised so emphatically, can be enjoyed by\nall families on an equal basis.\nThe possibilities for reemployment of a great\nmany who have suddenly been dismissed from\ntheir war jobs is good. It is a matter of shifting\nback from the ranks of government employment to\nthose of private enterprise.\nThese things may only occur if government\nwill adjust its economy to encourage the risk of\ncapital by private enterprise. If the two remain in\ncompetition, private enterprise will be the loser and\nunemployment will be with us again.\nIndications are to the contrary. The huge cor\nporations, controlled by the government, are slated\nfor a process of absorption by private enterprise.\nIt will mark the return of America to the very\nsystem which made it the great power it is today.\nGovernment control and the exigencies of war\nhave put us sorely in the red. The challenge to\nindustry and private enterprise is the turning of its\nv efforts to the new peace time economy of produc\ntion and industrial rehabilitation.\nThe plan is only workable by complete coop\neration of labor and industry. The ultimate result\nwill be a new prosperity and standard of living\nsuch as only America can evolve and maintain with\na proper place for all in the new national economy.\nMOTORISTS BEWARE!\nIt has been announced that the wartime lid\non speeding has been lifted. The new pace to be\ntolerated on our highways, acccording to State\nlaws, will vary from between forty to fifty miles\nper hour.\nIt is indeed a wise measure to keep speed laws\nout of the jurisdiction of federal control. Speeding\nin some of the sections of our country where no\ndense population is found may be comparatively\nsafe compared to parts like our Atlantic region.\nThere is no question but the highway fatali\nties have decreased since speed limits were lowered\non the national highways. Too great speed has\nbeen the cause of many fatal accidents.\nState and local regulations must at all times\nbe rigidly obeyed by the motoring public. With\nthe lifting of the rationing of motor fuels a new re\nsponsibility has fallen on the driver of any pleas\nure vehicle or truck.\nEast Hartford has maintained a splendid\nrecord of safety, due to the alert and efficient op\neration of our police department. We have done\nit without resorting to speed traps or any other un\npleasant methods.\nThere are two ways of impressing the motor\ning public with its obligation to drive safely on the\nroads and highways of our town. One is by calling\nthe other by showing no lenience or favoritism in\nattention to safe driving through local publicity,\nthe courtroom to evaders of the law.\nIn a great many cases the man behind the\nwheel is in a hurry without necessity. Statistics and\neven common sense show that the steady driver at\nmoderate pace arrives at his destination in the\nsame time as the rush and stop driver.\nThe protection of life and property on the\nhigway is a dual responsibility, equally shared be\ntween the local authorities and the driver.\nEast Hartford has done its share in promot\ning safety for our pedestrians and our children.\nWill Mr Motorist please check and remember his\npart?\nSCHOOL DAYS\nIn another week the schools of East Hartford\nwill reopen and receive their annual contingent of\nthe potential leaders of the future.\nTo the mothers at home it will mean the be\nginning of another year of careful guidance of the\nchildren through another chapter in their education.\nTo the teachers in the schools it means the\nexecution of another carefully prepared program\nof progrssive teaching.\nWith the changing picture of world events\nand the consequent changes in our preparation for\ncitizenship we must expect the continuous changes\nwhich occcur in each year\u2019s advanced ideas in\ntraining.\nA considerable number of teachers have been\nengaged in town who are starting their first year\nin our local schools. To them we send our best\nwishes for success and a pleasant and fruitful year\nin their new assignment.\nThe number of students in the various schools\nis still on the increase in comparison with the past\nyear. The smallest ones are going to get their first\ntouch of modern education, the ones in their final\nyears will grow into the new citizens who will soon\nbe called to apply their work in the schools to the\nproblems of every day life, or, if they determine\nto go on, to use it as a basis for college study and\ndevelopment.\nThe call to education and its value in the fu\nture has never been more clearly demonstrated\nthan in the final developments of the war behind us.\nIn spite of the many criticisms leveled at our sys\ntems of education, let us be diankful it was the\nAmerican ingenuity and application which gave us\nthe edge over our enemies.\nEducation as we see it today is the complex\nproblem of adjusting our younger generation to the\ntask of living useful and controlled lives in the en\nvironment of the ever changing world. As such its\nprogram must be both progressive and elastic. It\ncannot be the same tomorrow as it was yesterday.\nSchool days are here again. The future\ngrows from the experience of today. In the growth\nand perfection of our schools still lies the promise\nof the better tomorrow which lies inevitably ahead.\nPRISON INSTEAD OF DEATH\nCriminals who bum for profit, or burn as a\nresult of a form of mental derangement known as\n\u201cpyromania,\u2019 responsible for the loss of many\nlives and the destruction of millions of dollars\nworth of property every year.\nAs a means of checking incendiary fires, the\nNational Board of Fire Underwriters in 1873\nformed an Arson Committee \u201cto repress incendi\narism and arson.\u201d Meantime, scientific study of\nthe habits and methods of arsonists and pyroman\niacs revealed that unlike other crimes, which oc\ncur with a certain degree of regularity in most\ncommunities, arson may not occur in a town for\nyears. It would be too expensive, therefore, for the\naverage town or city to support special arson de\ntctives. The problem of tracing arsonists is fre\nquently interstate in character, and in 1917 the\nNational Board acted to establish a nationwide\narson department. The department has grown to a\nstaff of 80 field investigators and 20 clerical and\noperational employes.\nThe skilled staff is ready to help local po\nlice, law enforcement and fire prevention officials\nin the task of stamping out arson and incendiarism.\nThey operate in the public interest whether the\nproperty involved is insured or not. A report of\nth National Board\u2019s Committee on Incendiarism\nand Arson shows that during the last year 1,796\nfires of suspicious origin were investigated. Arrests\nduring the same period totaled 526. Three hun\ndred and sixteen arsonists x 're convicted.\nMost arsonists today are caught and con\nvicted. Under Roman and Old English law, death\nwas the penalty for arson. Today a stiff prison\nterm is an effective cure.\nSTILL THE BEST SYSTEM\nThe production of 100-octane aviation gas\noline by American refineries, has been one of the\nwonders of World War 11. It was discouraging\nto our enemies. It shows that brains and initiative\nare more important in winning wars, than dicta\ntors. It shows what American industry can do\nwhen called upon in an emergency. It not only\nhad to build the t plants to produce this high-test\ngasoline, but it had to perfect the processes by\nwhich it could be produced in quantity. It was\nready to \u201cgo,\u201d however, without entangling de\nlays.\nAmerican oil companies set a recc\u2019d that no\ngovernment-dominated industry could meet. It is\naccomplishments like this that should cause the\nAmerican people to be proud of their free enter\nprise system. Like all human activity, it may not\nbe perfect, and there is room for constant improv\nment, but so far no other system of industrial pro\nduction has been able to hold a candle to it.\nFurthermore, as in the case of oil, it is elastic and\nready to meet emergencies, instead of being bound\nby red tape and inefficincy which are unavoidable\nunder politically controlled industries where ex\npediency, from the standpoint of maintaining\nparty power, is too often more important than ef\nfidency.\nEAST HARTFORD GAZETTE, AUGUST 24, 1945.\nIn harmony with its policy of\nnot publishing anonymous let\nters, The Gazette will be glad to\npublish the letter signed \u201cG\u201d if\nthe writer will make his or her\nidentity known to the editor.\nESCOJOTI\nBOY.SCOUTS 4AI\nBY DANNY SHEA\nThe announcement by Salvage\nAuthorities this week, that the\ncollection of waste paper will\ncontinue, in spite of the end of\nthe war, has prompted troop\nleaders to go ahead with fall sal\nvage plans for their troops. Sev\neral troops collect paper regular\nly during the winter to boost\ntheir funds and, until further no\ntice, dealers will be ready to pur\nchase this paper from Scouts col\nlecting it.\nWith school only a week and a\nhalf away, Scouts are returning\nfrom vacations and rejoining\ntroops. Fall programs will get\nunderway with full force in Sep\ntember, and advanceemnt and\nrecruiting will be stressed during\nthe month. Leaders are urged to\nrecruit younger boys in their\ntroops at the beginning of the\nschool year to replace older ones\nwho may have left during the\nsummer months.\n\u2022\u2018llie Scout\u201d\nThe fifth issue of \u201cThe Scout\u201d\nwhich is published by this troop,\nwill be distributed at the begin\nning of September.\nFall Program\nPlans for the fall program of\nTroop 134 will be made at next\nweeks meeting by the Green Bar\nCouncil. Any members of the\ntroop having suggestions for the\nprogram should contact their pa\ntrol leader, who will bring them\nto the council.\nBlue Devils\nProportion and propriety are\namong the best secrets of domes\ntic wisdom; and there is no sur\ner test of integrity than a well\nproportioned expenditure. \u2014Han\nnah More.\nPleasures are all alike, simply\nconsidered in themselves. He\nthat takes pleasure to hear ser\nmons enjoys himself as much as\nhe that hears plays.\u2014John Sel\nden.\nNo pleasure is comparable to\nthe standing upon the vantage\nground of truth.\u2014Francis Bacon\nSearch for the truth is the no\nblest occupation of man; its pub\nlication is a duty.\u2014Mme. deStael\nWhat a man knows has to be\nput into action to really count.\u2014\nRoy L. Smith\nA man should never be asham\ned to own he has been in the\nwrong, which is but saying in\nother words that he is wiser to\nday than he was yesterday.\u2014\nPope\nLETTERS FROM\nGAZETTE READERS\nQUESTION\nDear Editor:\nIs the Frank J Nolan of 153\nMain Street, who was suspended\nfrom the Police Board on alleged\ncharges of attempted \u201cfixing\u201d of\na morals charge, the same man\nwho is heading East Hartford\u2019s\nDraft Board? Is he the same\nman who is a member of the\nDemocratic Town Committee?\nThe Town Council has evident\nly found cause to remove Mr. No\nlan from the Police Board, and\nif he is the same man who heads\nthe local Draft Board, I ques\ntion his fitness to have juris\ndiction of the calling of our\nsons for service in the Armed\nServices.\nFAIR PLAY.\nEast Hartford, Aug. 21, 1945\nThe district baseball league\nwill come to a close next week\nwhen the four leading teams\nmeet for the playoffs. This is\nthe second year that the league\nhas been successfully conducted\nhere, and next year the practice\nwill be continued, it is expected.\nTROOP 134\nBy Bobby Salls\nOvernight Camp\nAn overnight camp will be held\nnext Saturday to climax the end\nof the summer program. The\ntroop will go to Lake Terramug\ngus.\nAn outing for the Blue Devils\nbaseball team will be held next\nSaturday.\nThe Devils lost their first game\nin the second round Monday\nwhen the strong Troop 67 defeat\ned them 3 to 2, at Martin Field.\nMRS. WILLIAMS\nMr. and Mrs. Arthur Olsson of\nProvidence, R. L, spent the week\nwith Mrs. Marybelle Williams of\nChurch Street. Mrs. Williams\u2019\ngranddaughter, Miss Barbara\nWilljams, spent the week-end\nwith her.\nAt Sea\nA.\nTHOMAS McLAGAN\nChief Petty Officer Thomas\nMcLagan, U. S. Navy, son of the\nlate Thomas and Mrs. Myrtle\nMcLagan of 21 Terry Road is\nnow aboard the USS Whitney\nsomewhere on the high seas of\nthe Pacific. His first enlistment\nbegan in 1931, and he received\nhis boot training at Newport, R.\nI. Later he served aboard the\nUSS Minneapolis and while\ncruising, visited France, Holland,\nBelgium, England, Alaska. Pana\nma and the west coast, until\n1934. He re-enlisted in June, 1942\nand was stationed at Long\nBeach, L. I. for three years, be\nfore being shipped to the west\ncoast for patrol duty in the Pa\ncific area. Tom was married\nJune 18, 1938 and has a five year\nold son, Douglas. Prior to his\njoining the service the second\ntime he worked at Niles-Bement-\nPond in West Hartford.\nLEGAL NOTICE\nNOTICE\nRepublican electors of the sev\neral districts are hereby called to\nmeet in Caucus on Saturday, Sep\ntember 1, 1945 at 8 o\u2019cclock at\nthe following places:\nDistrict No. I\u2014Meeting at Sec\nond North School.\nDistrict No. 2\u2014Meeting at Mea\ndow School.\nDistrict No. 3\u2014Meeting at East\nHartford High School.\nDistrict No. 4\u2014Meeting at Burn\nside Grammar School.\nDistrict No. s\u2014Meetings\u2014Meeting at South\nGrammar School.\n1. For the purpose of acting\nupon the nomination of candi\ndates for councilmen from the\nvarious districts.\n2. For the purpose of select\ning delegates to a convention to\nbe held at the East Hartford\nHigh School on Thursday, Sep\ntember 6, 1945, at 9 P. M., to act\nupon nominations for candidates\nfor th^ various town offices and\nto act upon any other matters\nproper to come before said con\nvention.\nAll tickets for candidates for\ncouncilmen, and delegates to the\ntown convention, must be signed\nby the candidate for councilman\nand delegates to the Town Con\nvention and filed at least 72\nhours before the district caucus\nwith the district chairman and\nwith the chairman of the Town\nCommittee.\nBy order of the Republican\nTown Committee:\nGEORGE E. WOOD,\nChairman.\nDated at East Hartford\nAugust 20, 1945\nEAST HARTFORD\nTelephone 8-3231\nMothen...Sbop Now for Their\nSnow Suits\n5.98 to 19.50\nIt isn't too early to think of winter! Choose\nvour bov's or girl's snow suit now and use\nKKm our convcn cnt Lay-Away Plan.\nly One and two-piece styles sizes 1 to 14.\nW Little girls will love the famous Laskin\nlamb trimmed \u201cWeather Winky\u201d (pictur\ned) nationally advertised in Parents\u2019 Mag\nazine. Or if you prefer legging suits, we\nhave\nI\nSage-Allen's East Hartford Branch Store Is Open Every\nFriday Night 'Til 9P.M.\n||CHUACHES|\nCENTER METHODIST\nCHURCH\nRev. Meredith Eller, Pastor\nUnion Service with First Con\ngregational Church during the\nmonth of August. Service at 11\na. m. Speaker, Rev. Truman H.\nWoodward, pastor of First Con\ngregational Church.\nBURNSIDE METHODIST\nCHURCH\nRev. Nathan B. Burton, Pastor\nChurch School at 9:30.\nMorning worship at 10:45. Ser\nmon by the pastor.\nST. MARY\u2019S CHURCH\nRev. Thos J. Drennan, Pastor\nMasses at 7,8, 910 and 11\no\u2019clock.\nConfessions Saturday after\nnoon and evening.\nST. ROSE\u2019S CHURCH\nRev. Austin F. Munich, Pastor\nMasses at 7:30. 8:30, 10 and 11\no\u2019clock.\nMasses at Mayberry Village\nCommunity Building at 8 and 10\no\u2019clock.\nConfessions Saturday after\nnoon and evening.\nST. JOHN\u2019S CHURCH\nRev. James W. Lord, Pastor\n8:00 Holy Communion\n10:30 Morning Prayer\nSOUTH CONGREGATIONAL\nCHURCH\nRev. Read Chatterton, Minister\n10:00 Morning Worship; Rev.\nWillard T. Carter of Hartford\nSeminary, guest minister.\n18\u2014IN GI new cut\nRECOVERING\nMrs. Edward Johnson of 47\nBidwell Avenue returned home\nTuesday from Hartford Hospital\nwhere she underwent a minor\noperation. Her daughter-in-law,\nMrs. George Johnson of Man\nchester, is staying with her for\ntwo weeks.\nVACATIONING\nMr. and Mrs. Harold Tallman\nof Laraia Avenue are spending\ntwo weeks at Misquamicut, R. I.\nLT. COL. MANIERRE\nLieutenant Colonel and Mrs.\nErnest Manierre and family are\nvisiting his parents, Mr. and Mrs.\nErnest Manierre, of Birchwood\nRoad.\nI am now in a position to extend my services\nand offer you the finest in workmanship at\nmost reasonable cost. I welcome your inquiries\nfor all types of copy and restoration work with\nthe assurance of your complete satisfaction.\nSamples available for your inspection.\nHarold Clay, Photographer\nSpecialist in Reproductions and Restorations\n334 Silver Lane 8-1047 East Hartford\nEAST HARTFORD\n25 YEARS AGO\nFrom Gazette of August 20, 1920\nMr. and Mrs. Arthur Heimer\nentertained the following guests\nover the week-end at their cot\ntage in Pine Orchard: Mr. and\nMrs. Henry Pinriey, Mr. and Mrs.\nJohn Collins of Rockville, Mr.\nand Mrs. Harry Pinney of Broad\nBrook and Edward Heimer, Sr. of\nthis town.\nMiss Nan Fletcher spent the\nweek-end at her home on Spring\nStreet.\nThe Sadd House on Bumside\nAvenue has been purchased by\nHenry T. Curtiss of Olmsted\nStreet. Mr. Curtiss will occupy\nsame about September Ist\nHerbert Johnson of Burnside\nAvenue is at East Hampton for\na week\u2019s vacation.\nMr. and Mrs. Joseph Jones\nwere the recent guests of Mr. and\nMrs. Charles Gleason of Clinton.\nMr. and Mrs. Albert Stillman\nand daughter, Ruth, of Elm\nStreet, have returned from Wal\nnut Beach.\nMr. and Mrs. Nelson Smith of\nOlmsted Street left Tuesday for\na two weeks\u2019 motor trip through\nVermont.\nMr. and Mrs. T. E. Dwight and\nMr. and Mrs. Harry Hannon of\nElm Street are at Bolton Lake\nfor a few weeks.\nMrs. Mary Burke of Main\nStreet reported to the police Fri\nday morning that she had lost a\nsum of money Thursday after\nnoon about five o\u2019clock between\nSamuel Harrison\u2019s store and\nO\u2019Connell\u2019s Drug Store.\nThe engagement of Miss Paul\nine Spencer Ketchin, daughter of\nMr. and Mrs. William Ketchin of\nTarriffville, to Warren L. Hale,\nson of Henry B. Hale of Wells\nAvenue, was announced at a\nshower given in honor of Miss\nKetchin\u2019s sister, Miss Elizabeth\nKetchin, whose marriage to Ma\njor Frederick Herpel of the Unit\ned States Medical Unit is to take\nplace this fall. Miss Pauline\nKetchin is a graduate of Knox\nSchool, Tarrytown -on -the Hud\nson. Mr. Hale graduated from\nLeland Stanford University, Cal\nif., in 1914. He served overseas as\na pilot in the United States Air\nService.\nExpert prescription compound\ning, Noble, the Druggist, 1001\nMain Street.\u2014Adv.","height":"27217","width":"19862"}}
